moved` and sorting.\n        *   Then, define `result := { ... }`. This is where `removedCoherent := sorry` is used.\n4.  The goal is to prove `∀ (id : RequestId), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'`. This is a side condition for `List.insert` or similar operations that would be implicitly or explicitly required if `removed'` were constructed by `List.insert` or `List.append`.\n\nThe strategy of constructing `result` and then proving properties about it is standard. The issue is the unproven `removedCoherent` field. The `sorry` tactic means this sub-proof is incomplete.\n\nTo fix the `sorry` in `removedCoherent`, we need to provide a concrete proof term for the proposition that `removedCoherent` is supposed to represent. The proposition is `∀ (id : RequestId), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'`.\n\nLet's analyze the terms:\n*   `removed'` is `read' :: state.removed |>.toArray.qsort ...`. The elements of `removed'` are `read'` and the elements of `state.removed`.\n*   `reqIds requests'` is the list of `id` for each `r` in `requests'`.\n\nWe need to show that for any `id` in `List.map Request.id removed'`, that `id` is also in `reqIds requests'`.\n\nLet's consider the elements of `List.map Request.id removed'`:\n1.  `id(read')`: This is `readId`.\n2.  `id(r)` for each `r` in `state.removed`. These are the `id` values of the elements in `state.removed`.\n\nWe need to show:\n1.  `readId ∈ reqIds requests'`.\n2.  For each `r` in `state.removed`, `id(r) ∈ reqIds requests'`.\n\nLet's look at `requests'`:\n`requests'` is `state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId`.\nThe elements of `requests'` are the elements of `state.requests` that are not `readId`, plus any new elements introduced by `state.validateWrite`.\n\nWhen we `remove readId` from `state.requests`, we are removing an element. The `id` of this removed element is `readId`. So, `readId` is no longer in `requests'`.\nHowever, `readId` is in `List.map Request.id removed'` (as `id(read')`).\nSo we need to show `readId ∈ reqIds requests'`. This means `readId` must be an `id` of an element in `requests'`.\n\nThis suggests that `readId` must be added back to `requests'` somewhere, or our understanding is wrong.\nWait, `readId` is the index of the `read` operation. The `read` operation is `read'`. So `id(read') = readId`.\nAnd `read'` is constructed from `read` (which has `id = readId`) and `write` (which has `id = writeId`).\nSo `read'` is a new request, which will have `id = readId` (if `readId` is not used by another request).\nWait, the `id` of a request is fixed when it's created. So `read'` will have `id = readId`.\nSo `readId` is the `id` of `read'`.\nAnd `read'` is in `state.requests` after `state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId` if `read'` was already in `state.requests` before `remove readId`.\nWait, `read'` is defined *after* `requests'` is defined via `state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId`.\nSo `read'` is not in `state.requests` when `requests'` is computed via `state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId`.\nThis means `readId` is removed from `state.requests` in the computation of `requests'`.\nSo `readId` is not in `requests'`.\nThis means `readId ∉ reqIds requests'`.\nBut we need to show `readId ∈ List.map Request.id removed'`.\n`List.map Request.id removed'` is `[id(read'), id(r₁), id(r₂), ...]` where `r₁, r₂, ...` are the elements of `state.removed`.\nSince `id(read') = readId`, `readId` is indeed in `List.map Request.id removed'`.\nSo we need to show `readId ∈ reqIds requests'`.\nBut `requests'` is `state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId`.\nThe elements of `requests'` are the elements of `state.requests` that are not `readId`.\nSo `readId` is not in `reqIds requests'`.\nThis means the proposition `∀ (id : RequestId), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'` is false.\nThis indicates a flaw in the construction of `result` or the proof.\n\nWait, the definition of `