d`.\nSo `read'` is not in `state.requests` when `requests'` is computed.\nTherefore, `readId` is not in `reqIds requests'`.\n\nThe only way to make `readId` be in `reqIds requests'` is if `read'` is added back to `state.requests` before `requests'` is computed, or if `readId` is not removed.\nLooking at the code:\n`let requests' := state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId`\nThis removes `readId`.\nThen later:\n`let result := { ... }`\nThe `result` has `removed := removed'`.\n`removed'` is `read' :: state.removed |>.toArray.qsort ...`.\nSo `read'` is in `removed'`.\nBut `read'` is not in `requests'`.\nSo the side condition `∀ (id : ...), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'` is false.\nThe proof cannot be completed as written.\n\nThe fundamental issue is the structure of the proof term. Instead of trying to construct a complex proof term for `result`, we can use a different approach.\n\nInstead of:\n```tactics\nlet result := { ... }\nexact result\n```\nWe can use tactics to prove the goal directly. The goal is `∀ (id : RequestId), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'`.\n\nWe can try to prove this directly using tactics.\n```tactics\nintro id h\nhave h1 : id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' := h\n```\nNow we need to show `id ∈ reqIds requests'`.\n\nWe can use `rcases` on `h1`.\n`h1` is `id ∈ List.map Request.id removed'`.\n`List.map` is defined recursively. `List.map f (x :: xs)` is `f x :: List.map f xs`.\n`List.map` applied to `removed'` which is `read' :: state.removed |>.toArray.qsort ...`.\nSo `List.map Request.id removed'` is `id(read') :: List.map Request.id (state.removed |>.toArray.qsort ...)`.\n\nLet's use `simp` and `rcases` to break down `h1`.\n```tactics\nsimp [List.mem_map] at h1\n```\nAfter this, `h1` becomes `id = id(read') ∨ id ∈ List.map ...`.\nWe can `rcases h1 with (h1 | h1)`.\nIn the first case, `h1 : id = id(read')`.\nIn the second case, `h1 : id ∈ List.map ...`.\n\nLet's handle the first case:\n```t