      "\ndef SystemState.satisfy : SystemState → RequestId → RequestId → SystemState\n | state, readId, writeId =>\n let opRead := state.requests.getReq? readId\n let opWrite := state.requests.getReq? writeId\n match opRead, opWrite with\n   | some read, some write =>\n     let satisfied' := (readId,writeId)::state.satisfied |>.toArray.qsort lexBLe |>.toList\n     let read' := read.setValue write.value?\n     -- update rmwWrites\n     let requests' := state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId\n     let removed' := read'::state.removed |>.toArray.qsort\n       (λ r₁ r₂ => Nat.ble r₁.id r₂.id) |>.toList\n     let result := { requests := requests', orderConstraints := state.orderConstraints,\n                     removed := removed', satisfied := satisfied',\n                     threadTypes := state.threadTypes, removedCoherent := sorry,\n```\n\nThe error occurs because the field `removedCoherent` in the `result` system state is set to `sorry`. This means that the proof for `∀ (id : RequestId), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'` (which is the proposition that `removed'` is a subset of `requests'`) is incomplete.\n\nThe goal `⊢ ∀ (id : RequestId), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'` is a subset condition. It states that every element in the list `removed'` (which is `List.map Request.id (read'::state.removed)` i.e., `[read'.id] ++ state.removed.map (fun r => r.id)`) must also be an element of the list `requests'` (which is `List.map (fun r => r.id) (state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId)` i.e., `(state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId).map (fun r => r.id)`).\n\nTo prove this, we need to show that for any `id` in `List.map Request.id removed'`, `id` is also in `List.map (fun r => r.id) requests'`.\n\nLet's analyze `removed'` and `requests'`:\n\n- `removed'` is `List.map (fun r => r.id) (read' :: state.removed)`. This means `removed' = [read'.id] ++ state.removed.map (fun r => r.id)`.\n- `requests'` is `List.map (fun r => r.id) (state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId)`.\n\nFor `id ∈ List.map (fun r => r.id) (read' :: state.removed)`:\n- If `id = read'.id`, then we need to show `read'.id ∈ List.map (fun r => r.id) (state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId)`. This means `read'` must be in the list `state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId`.\n- If `id ∈ state.removed.map (fun r => r.id)`, then `id = r.id` for some `r ∈ state.removed`. We need to show `r.id ∈ List.map (fun r' => r'.id) (state |>.validateWrite writeId |>.remove readId)`.\n\nLet's look at the construction of `requests'`:\n`state |>.validateWrite writeId` produces a new list of requests, let's call it `valWrites`.\n`valWrites |>.remove readId` removes `readId` (if it exists) from `valWrites`.\n\nSo, `requests'` is `(valWrites \\ {readId}).map (fun r => r.id)`.\n\nAnd `removed'` is `(read' :: state.removed).map (fun r => r.id)`.\n\nFor `id ∈ removed'`:\n- `id = read'.id`. Is `read'.id ∈ requests'`? `read'.id` is the id of `read'`. If `read'` is in `valWrites \\ {readId}`, then yes. `read'` is `read.setValue write.value?`. `read` is from `state.requests`. So `read'.id = read.id`. Is `read.id ∈ valWrites`? Yes, because `valWrites` is `state |>.validateWrite writeId` and `read` is a request in `state`. Is `read.id ≠ readId`? Not necessarily. If `read.id = readId`, then `read'` is `read`. Then `read'.id = readId`. Is `readId ∈ valWrites \\ {readId}`? No, because `valWrites \\ {readId}` removes `readId` from `valWrites`. So `readId` is not in `valWrites \\ {readId}`. Therefore, `read'.id` (which is `readId`) is not in `requests'`.\n\nThis means that `removed'` is not a subset of `requests'`, so the proposition `∀ (id : RequestId), id ∈ List.map Request.id removed' → id ∈ reqIds requests'` is false. This is why Lean is stuck with a `sorry`.\n\nThe issue is that `satisfy` is defined as:\n`{ requests := requests', orderConstraints := state.orderConstraints, removed := removed', satisfied